1
00:02:17,240 --> 00:02:19,080
- Congressman.
- General.

2
00:02:48,440 --> 00:02:51,240
Herzlich Willkommen in Berlin.

3
00:02:55,400 --> 00:02:56,800
Who is that guy?

4
00:02:56,960 --> 00:02:59,880
It's Breimer. He's a congressman.

5
00:03:00,800 --> 00:03:03,680
- You're here for the peace conference?
- To write about it.

6
00:03:03,880 --> 00:03:07,160
- You ever hear of The New Republic?
- No.

7
00:03:07,920 --> 00:03:10,800
The uniform
is the Army's idea of a joke.

8
00:03:12,200 --> 00:03:14,600
You see any action?

9
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:17,880
I was in London when Franz Bettmann
aimed his Roman candles...

10
00:03:18,080 --> 00:03:22,320
...about a hundred feet away from me.
Broke all my martini glasses.

11
00:03:23,120 --> 00:03:25,600
Who is Franz Bettmann?

12
00:03:25,800 --> 00:03:27,880
Bettmann, Von Braun.

13
00:03:28,080 --> 00:03:30,760
The Kraut brain trust,
the guys who built the V-2s.

14
00:03:30,960 --> 00:03:33,800
I actually wrote a column about it.

15
00:03:34,080 --> 00:03:35,720
I wish I could write.

16
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:39,360
I have some great stories I could tell.

17
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:44,400
No sense beating up on the Germans.
The Russians are the enemy now.

18
00:03:44,400 --> 00:03:47,680
They're godless people. Go down
to the rail yard and see for yourself.

19
00:03:47,880 --> 00:03:51,120
Anything's not nailed down, they're
taking it, sending it to Moscow.

20
00:03:51,160 --> 00:03:53,320
Well, why not?
They took most of the bullets.

21
00:03:53,560 --> 00:03:57,280
We've been teaching the Ivans to play
ball. Some of those fellas can really hit.

22
00:03:57,480 --> 00:03:59,600
I bet you can't wait
to go home, huh, soldier?

23
00:03:59,760 --> 00:04:02,560
Yes, sir. You know the Germans.
They make excellent Danish...

24
00:04:02,560 --> 00:04:05,000
...but they can't bake apple pie
like my mom.

25
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:07,320
Nothing wrong with the Germans.

26
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:09,920
Plenty of good German folk
back in Schenectady.

27
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,160
Oh, excuse me.
Let me help you with that, sir.

28
00:04:32,360 --> 00:04:33,960
I got it, Tully.

29
00:04:34,160 --> 00:04:37,000
- Being helpful is all.
- You know who's driving me tomorrow?

30
00:04:37,040 --> 00:04:40,720
Got my trip ticket. I'm your driver
for the duration of your stay in Berlin.

31
00:04:40,880 --> 00:04:43,520
And I got you...

32
00:04:43,680 --> 00:04:46,000
...a little housewarming present.

33
00:04:46,200 --> 00:04:47,680
Thanks, Tully.

34
00:04:47,880 --> 00:04:52,160
- See you in the morning. Say, 0800?
-0800.

35
00:04:54,680 --> 00:04:58,400
I wouldn't myself have sized him up that
way, you know? Just meeting the guy...

36
00:04:58,600 --> 00:05:02,320
...you wouldn't think of him as a patsy.
That's what I loved about Berlin:

37
00:05:02,360 --> 00:05:06,080
Even a guy who wasn't a patsy back
home turned into one. It was inevitable.

38
00:05:06,840 --> 00:05:08,040
The city spread its legs.

39
00:05:08,240 --> 00:05:11,200
All that "eat, drink and be merry"
bullshit, "seize the day. "

40
00:05:11,400 --> 00:05:13,240
It sure didn't make anyone smarter.

41
00:05:13,440 --> 00:05:15,480
And the best part of it
was no one got hurt.

42
00:05:15,480 --> 00:05:18,040
There was too much money around
for anybody to fall...

43
00:05:18,240 --> 00:05:19,840
...without a nice soft cushion.

44
00:05:20,040 --> 00:05:23,840
Occupation marks printed just for us.
Funny money.

45
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:26,720
It didn't feel like losing it
when they lost it.

46
00:05:26,920 --> 00:05:29,440
The Russians, they had to spend it
before they went home.

47
00:05:29,640 --> 00:05:31,800
Which was all anyone talked about:
Going home.

48
00:05:31,840 --> 00:05:35,600
Everyone, even the Russians.
God, who would ever want to?

49
00:05:35,800 --> 00:05:37,480
Say what you want about the war.

50
00:05:37,480 --> 00:05:40,400
I would never wish
for all those millions of people to die...

51
00:05:40,600 --> 00:05:44,280
...but the war was the best thing
that ever happened to me.

52
00:05:44,480 --> 00:05:47,400
When you have money, then,
for the first time in your life...

53
00:05:47,600 --> 00:05:50,560
...you understand it,
what money does for you.

54
00:05:51,160 --> 00:05:54,760
Where before all you understood
was not having it.

55
00:05:54,920 --> 00:05:58,840
Money allows you
to be who you truly are.

56
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:07,440
So you like your job?

57
00:06:07,920 --> 00:06:09,160
What?

58
00:06:09,160 --> 00:06:10,680
Your job.

59
00:06:12,520 --> 00:06:13,720
Sure.

60
00:06:13,920 --> 00:06:15,880
Yeah?

61
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:19,520
What are you doing
with that cigarette?

62
00:06:19,720 --> 00:06:22,240
Waste not, want not.

63
00:06:22,440 --> 00:06:24,320
It is a job, right?

64
00:06:24,520 --> 00:06:27,200
How do you like your job?

65
00:06:27,600 --> 00:06:30,080
How do you like working
in the motor pool?

66
00:06:32,120 --> 00:06:33,560
What the hell does that mean?

67
00:06:34,520 --> 00:06:36,400
- Nothing.
- That doesn't even follow.

68
00:06:37,040 --> 00:06:38,120
Perhaps my English.

69
00:06:38,320 --> 00:06:41,640
Like you should be fucking Dwight
Eisenhower, Countess Roundheels?

70
00:06:41,800 --> 00:06:43,920
- I was making conversation.
- No, you weren't.

71
00:06:44,120 --> 00:06:46,480
That's what I was doing.
Don't tell me my business.

72
00:06:46,720 --> 00:06:49,120
Two thousand yards of silk
in the Russian zone.

73
00:06:49,280 --> 00:06:51,800
I get in and out anywhere.
The British zone, the French.

74
00:06:51,960 --> 00:06:55,120
I got the vehicle. The motor pool's
the best job in the fucking Army!

75
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:57,120
I'm sorry.

76
00:07:31,560 --> 00:07:34,480
I thought you were going to help me
get out of Germany.

77
00:07:34,520 --> 00:07:38,280
It's gonna get harder,
not easier. Watch.

78
00:07:39,240 --> 00:07:43,000
They put your name on a list,
and then that's it.

79
00:07:52,600 --> 00:07:56,560
I forget sometimes
what a boy you are.

80
00:07:57,120 --> 00:07:59,720
Such a boy.

81
00:08:02,200 --> 00:08:04,320
- A sweet little boy.
- No, cut it out.

82
00:08:04,360 --> 00:08:06,240
Does that bother you?

83
00:08:06,280 --> 00:08:08,120
Why should it?

84
00:08:08,360 --> 00:08:11,320
My husband was a boy too.

85
00:08:12,480 --> 00:08:16,240
A little boy
who saw numbers in his head.

86
00:08:23,480 --> 00:08:25,600
I'm your fellow, okay?

87
00:08:25,760 --> 00:08:28,240
I'll get you out of here.

88
00:08:28,800 --> 00:08:31,160
You watch.

89
00:08:36,520 --> 00:08:39,160
My gill,
she's not just a pretty face, no, sir.

90
00:08:39,400 --> 00:08:43,240
She won first prize last year with her
rhubarb pie, and second with her gourds.

91
00:08:43,480 --> 00:08:46,520
- That's terrific, Tully.
- Oh, she's pretty terrific, sir.

92
00:08:46,760 --> 00:08:48,960
Any luck, I'll be home
for the harvest dance.

93
00:08:49,120 --> 00:08:51,640
Well, at this rate
we'll still be driving to Potsdam.

94
00:08:52,440 --> 00:08:54,840
Somebody got up
on the wrong side of the bed.

95
00:08:55,040 --> 00:08:57,960
- Some son of a bitch stole my wallet.
- No kidding.

96
00:08:58,160 --> 00:09:01,560
It must have been
in that crowd at the airport.

97
00:09:01,800 --> 00:09:03,480
I can loan you money if you need it.

98
00:09:05,280 --> 00:09:06,600
Thanks, Tully.

99
00:09:06,600 --> 00:09:09,680
Don't want you to miss
all the great things Berlin has to offer.

100
00:09:09,920 --> 00:09:12,080
I used to live here before the war.

101
00:09:12,360 --> 00:09:14,400
- Really?
- Ran the AP bureau.

102
00:09:15,920 --> 00:09:18,600
They're not really gonna put
the country on trial, are they?

103
00:09:18,800 --> 00:09:20,400
Do you think they shouldn't?

104
00:09:20,600 --> 00:09:22,600
Doesn't seem American
to lock a person up...

105
00:09:22,760 --> 00:09:25,480
...for something they didn't
have anything to do with.

106
00:09:26,960 --> 00:09:28,720
Somebody you know, Tully?

107
00:09:30,040 --> 00:09:31,560
I'm just saying.

108
00:09:31,600 --> 00:09:35,160
Well, there's a piece that would sell:
"Fallen Women of the Third Reich. "

109
00:09:36,320 --> 00:09:37,520
That's pretty raw, sir.

110
00:09:37,720 --> 00:09:41,120
Millions of people didn't disappear
because the elves came out at night.

111
00:09:41,200 --> 00:09:44,800
Your Fraulein knew exactly
what Hitler was doing. They all knew.

112
00:09:44,840 --> 00:09:47,840
- Did she lift a finger?
- You don't know a thing about her.

113
00:09:47,880 --> 00:09:49,360
And you do?

114
00:09:50,120 --> 00:09:52,520
Just because you're a German
doesn't make you a Nazi.

115
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:02,120
You heard Breimer.
It's on to the Russians.

116
00:10:02,160 --> 00:10:04,120
The next war.

117
00:10:04,160 --> 00:10:08,000
They'll leave your girlfriend alone unless
there's some special reason not to.

118
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:10,360
It's gonna cost me
to get her out of Germany...

119
00:10:10,520 --> 00:10:12,760
...I can tell you that right now.

120
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:15,040
I wish I could help you out, kid.

121
00:10:17,080 --> 00:10:18,320
You want an hour with her?

122
00:11:22,720 --> 00:11:25,240
Beautiful day, huh?

123
00:11:25,440 --> 00:11:28,280
Are you looking for an argument?

124
00:11:33,240 --> 00:11:36,720
I'm sorry I broke your tooth.
It was an honest disagreement.

125
00:11:36,920 --> 00:11:38,080
What do you need?

126
00:11:38,280 --> 00:11:41,120
Papers.
To get someone out of Germany.

127
00:11:41,320 --> 00:11:44,560
- A Nazi?
- Not a Nazi. A friend of mine.

128
00:11:44,760 --> 00:11:47,920
With what I've been through, you'd
ask me to help a Nazi escape Germany?

129
00:11:48,160 --> 00:11:50,080
Hey, cry me a river.

130
00:11:50,280 --> 00:11:54,600
Fuck, everyone in this town's
got a hard-luck story.

131
00:11:56,960 --> 00:11:59,560
You gonna help me or not?

132
00:12:03,880 --> 00:12:05,320
I'll see what I can do.

133
00:12:05,520 --> 00:12:07,920
Great. Just don't Jew me on the price.

134
00:12:51,480 --> 00:12:53,400
Lena?

135
00:13:06,760 --> 00:13:10,080
- Where's Emil Brandt?
- Who?

136
00:13:10,520 --> 00:13:14,440
- Emil Brandt.
- Who the fuck is Emil Brandt?

137
00:13:14,920 --> 00:13:16,800
- Where's Emil Brandt?
- Fuck you!

138
00:13:25,240 --> 00:13:26,640
Fuck!

139
00:13:55,040 --> 00:13:56,160
Who's Emil Brandt?

140
00:13:56,320 --> 00:13:58,280
- Emil?
- Who is he?

141
00:13:58,520 --> 00:14:01,360
They were looking for him
in your place, Lena. Where is he?

142
00:14:01,600 --> 00:14:04,240
- He's dead.
- Don't lie to me!

143
00:14:04,440 --> 00:14:06,160
He died.

144
00:14:06,360 --> 00:14:07,760
He died in the war.

145
00:14:07,800 --> 00:14:10,600
Like you fucking know! Who is he?

146
00:14:10,800 --> 00:14:13,040
He was my husband.

147
00:14:13,200 --> 00:14:15,320
Lena?

148
00:14:21,520 --> 00:14:25,640
- Emil Brandt. That's your husband?
- Yes.

149
00:14:26,120 --> 00:14:27,560
I'm Lena Brandt.

150
00:14:28,440 --> 00:14:31,040
- A last name. What a cozy feeling.
- Tully-

151
00:14:31,280 --> 00:14:34,040
He must have done something
if they're hopped up to find him.

152
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:37,120
I'm gonna find out sooner or later!

153
00:14:37,320 --> 00:14:39,000
He was a mathematician.

154
00:14:39,200 --> 00:14:42,440
He saw numbers in his head?
It's bullshit! They broke my fucking arm!

155
00:14:42,640 --> 00:14:44,000
He was a nobody.

156
00:14:44,200 --> 00:14:46,120
- Somebody's secretary.
- Whose secretary?

157
00:14:46,320 --> 00:14:48,080
What does it matter who?

158
00:14:48,280 --> 00:14:50,560
My husband brought him his coffee
and took steno.

159
00:14:50,760 --> 00:14:52,400
When's the last time you saw him?

160
00:14:52,600 --> 00:14:54,280
Three- Three years ago.

161
00:14:54,480 --> 00:14:56,120
I'm with you now, Tully.

162
00:14:56,280 --> 00:14:58,920
How am I supposed to help you, Lena,
if you won't help me?

163
00:15:00,480 --> 00:15:03,280
I would never hurt you, Tully.

164
00:15:03,920 --> 00:15:06,040
Never.

165
00:15:10,720 --> 00:15:12,560
You can get anything
on the black market.

166
00:15:13,080 --> 00:15:15,680
I talked to someone.
A little lop-cock, no legs...

167
00:15:15,840 --> 00:15:17,440
...but he can run down anything.

168
00:15:17,640 --> 00:15:20,600
He can get you on a train out.
That's what you want, right?

169
00:15:21,120 --> 00:15:24,160
They told me he was dead.

170
00:15:24,840 --> 00:15:28,440
One more dead, or not dead.

171
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:31,160
Who would know?

172
00:15:34,680 --> 00:15:37,720
Poor, fucking stupid Lena.

173
00:15:38,880 --> 00:15:41,920
You don't know fucking nothing,
do you?

174
00:16:23,080 --> 00:16:24,760
Hey, Sikorsky.

175
00:16:24,960 --> 00:16:27,360
What happened to your arm?

176
00:16:27,600 --> 00:16:31,120
Scotch from Scotland. Forty cases.

177
00:16:32,520 --> 00:16:33,520
Good?

178
00:16:33,720 --> 00:16:36,320
They flew it in for Churchill.

179
00:16:37,920 --> 00:16:39,240
Can't afford it.

180
00:16:39,520 --> 00:16:43,600
Hey, who's your comrade?
Don't worry, I'll give you a price.

181
00:16:56,520 --> 00:16:58,960
I got something else for you.

182
00:16:59,160 --> 00:17:01,160
Really? What's that?

183
00:17:01,360 --> 00:17:02,560
Emil Brandt.

184
00:17:05,160 --> 00:17:06,440
Remind me who that is.

185
00:17:07,120 --> 00:17:09,120
You should know.
You've been looking for him.

186
00:17:09,320 --> 00:17:10,560
Have I?

187
00:17:12,480 --> 00:17:15,640
Names, names, so many names.

188
00:17:15,880 --> 00:17:18,520
Maybe I should just turn him over
to the Americans.

189
00:17:18,520 --> 00:17:19,800
Why don't you?

190
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:22,280
Because when everyone else
pulls up their tents...

191
00:17:22,480 --> 00:17:25,480
...you Ivans will be the only game
in Berlin, and the fact is...

192
00:17:25,680 --> 00:17:28,320
- ... I like it here.
- That's it?

193
00:17:28,520 --> 00:17:30,880
A favor?

194
00:17:34,240 --> 00:17:35,480
Two hundred thousand marks.

195
00:17:38,560 --> 00:17:42,760
It's not like I'm asking for real money.
Have the printing press work overtime.

196
00:17:43,400 --> 00:17:46,280
Plus papers, so I can get my girlfriend
on a train out of here.

197
00:17:46,960 --> 00:17:48,480
The trouble is, Tully...

198
00:17:48,680 --> 00:17:52,480
...I have seen Emil Brandt's
death certificate with my own eyes.

199
00:17:53,480 --> 00:17:56,600
I thought you weren't looking for him.

200
00:18:05,600 --> 00:18:08,280
Now, let me do you a favor.

201
00:18:08,320 --> 00:18:13,280
You remind me of my son, a little bit
of a buffoon, but good-natured.

202
00:18:13,520 --> 00:18:17,120
Get out. Now. Before you get hurt.

203
00:18:29,960 --> 00:18:31,520
Suit yourself.

204
00:18:31,680 --> 00:18:35,200
I just gotta figure out
how to get my girlfriend on that train.

205
00:18:36,280 --> 00:18:37,640
What's your girlfriend's name?

206
00:18:40,080 --> 00:18:42,240
Mrs. Emil Brandt.

207
00:18:42,440 --> 00:18:46,000
Imagine her surprise
when he turned up like that.

208
00:18:46,280 --> 00:18:48,400
And mine too.

209
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:56,280
Hey, Tully.

210
00:19:01,880 --> 00:19:04,080
I'll take your offer.

211
00:19:04,080 --> 00:19:06,440
Two hundred thousand marks.

212
00:19:08,040 --> 00:19:12,080
A lot to arrange, getting him out
of the American zone. You follow?

213
00:19:13,440 --> 00:19:17,200
Come back in two hours.
I'll advance you half.

214
00:19:17,400 --> 00:19:19,440
And bring Mrs. Brandt.

215
00:19:47,240 --> 00:19:49,200
I'm not going with you
to the Russian zone.

216
00:19:49,400 --> 00:19:51,880
Lena, half up front,
100,000 marks.

217
00:19:52,080 --> 00:19:53,960
Have you checked
the exchange rate lately?

218
00:19:54,000 --> 00:19:56,480
What happens when they find out
you don't have Emil?

219
00:19:56,720 --> 00:19:59,560
What happens is, we're in London
with 10,000 fucking dollars.

220
00:19:59,760 --> 00:20:01,880
You're out, I'm out.
It's a perfect plan.

221
00:20:02,120 --> 00:20:03,920
I won't go to the Russian zone.
I won't.

222
00:20:04,440 --> 00:20:08,160
He just wants to see you. What's the
big deal? He wants to know I have him.

223
00:20:08,360 --> 00:20:12,080
- But you don't have him.
- You're out selling love you don't have.

224
00:20:15,120 --> 00:20:16,760
Hey, fish.

225
00:20:16,960 --> 00:20:19,480
I had to hitch a ride
from the conference. What happened?

226
00:20:19,680 --> 00:20:20,760
Blow.

227
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:24,320
I hate to pull rank on you,
but you are my fucking driver.

228
00:20:25,040 --> 00:20:26,600
I'm off the clock, sir.

229
00:20:34,920 --> 00:20:36,040
Lena?

230
00:20:44,840 --> 00:20:46,480
I'm off the clock too.

231
00:20:47,360 --> 00:20:50,320
I'll pick you up in the morning.
I'm in the middle of something.

232
00:20:50,520 --> 00:20:52,880
- We know each other.
- I'm in the middle of something.

233
00:20:53,080 --> 00:20:55,560
- What happened to you?
- I need a minute to think, Tully.

234
00:20:55,760 --> 00:20:58,240
You can think on the way.

235
00:20:58,240 --> 00:21:01,120
- Hey, don't push her around like that.
- Fuck you!

236
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:04,120
Move!

237
00:21:11,240 --> 00:21:12,680
Get in.

238
00:21:12,880 --> 00:21:14,960
Hey!

239
00:21:17,600 --> 00:21:19,320
- Tully, stop.
- Shut up!

240
00:21:21,200 --> 00:21:22,520
Stupid fuck!

241
00:21:35,720 --> 00:21:39,360
They gave me a choice:
London or Berlin.

242
00:21:39,400 --> 00:21:41,320
For me there was no choice.

243
00:21:41,320 --> 00:21:44,880
The minute it came over the wire
that the war in Europe was finally over...

244
00:21:45,080 --> 00:21:47,400
...all I thought of was Lena.

245
00:21:48,240 --> 00:21:50,560
I didn't expect to run into her.
Not that way.

246
00:21:50,760 --> 00:21:52,840
Not my first week in town.

247
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:55,320
