in the bombing.

490
00:47:51,960 --> 00:47:54,280
Tully found out the Americans
were looking for Emil...

491
00:47:54,480 --> 00:47:58,760
...so he offered him to the Russians.
One of his schemes. Stupid.

492
00:47:59,000 --> 00:48:02,440
A way to get money to get me
out of Germany. Sell them a dead man.

493
00:48:02,600 --> 00:48:05,720
Now he's dead too. Maybe you next,
if you don't watch yourself.

494
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:08,040
This isn't gonna go away
because Tully's dead.

495
00:48:08,280 --> 00:48:10,200
- That's all I know.
- Emil was with the SS?

496
00:48:10,400 --> 00:48:11,960
Two years ago they all got uniforms.

497
00:48:12,200 --> 00:48:13,600
- Who knows why?
- Stop lying to me.

498
00:48:13,800 --> 00:48:17,000
I'm a Nazi myself, did you know that?
It's true.

499
00:48:17,080 --> 00:48:19,400
- You're not a Nazi.
- No, not a Nazi. None of us.

500
00:48:19,560 --> 00:48:21,720
Just something to join,
like a sport club.

501
00:48:21,920 --> 00:48:24,760
How could you fuck someone
for all those years and not know them?

502
00:48:24,960 --> 00:48:27,040
- Stop it.
- Did you ever fuck a Nazi?

503
00:48:27,280 --> 00:48:28,680
- Cut it out.
- How about a Jew?

504
00:48:28,720 --> 00:48:31,920
- Why won't you let me help you?
- A Nazi and a Jew both, better yet.

505
00:48:32,200 --> 00:48:35,440
- You did nothing wrong!
- I survived.

506
00:49:13,720 --> 00:49:16,440
What happened
to the rest of your family?

507
00:49:17,200 --> 00:49:19,680
They got sent to the camps.

508
00:49:19,880 --> 00:49:23,960
Everyone. My mother, uncles, cousins.

509
00:49:24,120 --> 00:49:26,280
Everyone dead.

510
00:49:26,520 --> 00:49:29,440
As the wife of an SS man...

511
00:49:29,600 --> 00:49:31,160
...I was exempt.

512
00:49:31,360 --> 00:49:35,280
"A Jewess is not a Jew,"
that's the way they used to put it.

513
00:49:36,160 --> 00:49:39,280
It's not something
I have ever told anyone.

514
00:49:40,680 --> 00:49:42,720
And at the end...

515
00:49:43,440 --> 00:49:45,920
...no one was exempt.

516
00:49:47,480 --> 00:49:52,120
Hannelore told me
that you were raped by a Russian?

517
00:49:52,320 --> 00:49:54,680
Hannelore can't tell a joke.

518
00:49:54,880 --> 00:49:58,280
- I didn't realize it was funny.
- Hannelore's funny.

519
00:49:58,480 --> 00:50:02,120
- She always leaves something out.
- Why?

520
00:50:02,520 --> 00:50:04,600
What did she leave out?

521
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:25,880
And then I met Tully.

522
00:50:44,360 --> 00:50:48,160
God in heaven, I never thought
I'd eat real ham again.

523
00:50:50,640 --> 00:50:52,280
Aren't you gonna have any?

524
00:50:52,480 --> 00:50:54,880
- None for me.
- No?

525
00:50:55,280 --> 00:50:57,800
Is that a Jewish name, Jacob?

526
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:00,480
The way you're eating that ham
could turn anyone kosher.

527
00:51:04,920 --> 00:51:07,880
It's easy now to say Hitler
was wrong about the Jews.

528
00:51:07,880 --> 00:51:12,440
Let me tell you something.
Nobody said he was wrong at the time.

529
00:51:18,280 --> 00:51:19,560
You're up early.

530
00:51:21,440 --> 00:51:23,760
I went down to the PX first thing
and stocked up.

531
00:51:23,920 --> 00:51:25,080
Do you want some coffee?

532
00:51:26,600 --> 00:51:28,560
Real coffee.

533
00:51:29,160 --> 00:51:31,840
No wonder you won the war,
eating like this.

534
00:51:32,360 --> 00:51:35,160
The little girl in the photograph,
is that Dora?

535
00:51:35,640 --> 00:51:37,440
The notebook said "Dora. "

536
00:51:37,480 --> 00:51:40,320
What do you think you'll find in here?

537
00:51:40,360 --> 00:51:42,840
It's all I have left of him.

538
00:51:44,760 --> 00:51:49,000
Very dramatic, the princess.

539
00:51:50,400 --> 00:51:52,080
Don't believe her.

540
00:51:52,320 --> 00:51:54,920
She didn't give two shits for him,
alive or dead.

541
00:51:55,120 --> 00:51:57,960
Dragging around that shrine
of crap and papers.

542
00:51:58,240 --> 00:52:01,360
Meanwhile, fucking with you
the whole time before the war.

543
00:52:02,480 --> 00:52:04,480
She'd make you a good wife, Lena.

544
00:52:04,680 --> 00:52:07,280
She knows all the tricks.

545
00:52:19,000 --> 00:52:20,840
At ease.

546
00:52:21,040 --> 00:52:23,320
Jake, come on into my office.

547
00:52:27,400 --> 00:52:31,520
It takes two MPs to invite a friend over?
No wonder you don't get many dates.

548
00:52:31,720 --> 00:52:34,280
You haven't been home
the last couple of nights. How come?

549
00:52:34,480 --> 00:52:36,920
- Keeping tabs on me, Bernie?
- Those are classified.

550
00:52:37,080 --> 00:52:38,080
I can keep a secret.

551
00:52:38,280 --> 00:52:40,560
What the hell happened between you
and Sikorsky?

552
00:52:40,720 --> 00:52:41,880
Who's asking, you or Muller?

553
00:52:42,480 --> 00:52:45,520
Don't be stupid.
Muller thought I should arrest you.

554
00:52:45,680 --> 00:52:47,080
Like you just did?

555
00:52:47,680 --> 00:52:49,640
What happened to your ear?

556
00:52:49,960 --> 00:52:53,000
Sikorsky says it's safer for me
on the Russian side than on ours.

557
00:52:53,240 --> 00:52:56,120
- I'm starting to think he's right.
- What else did Sikorsky say?

558
00:52:56,160 --> 00:52:59,000
Come on, I show up in Berlin,
and the driver assigned to me...

559
00:52:59,200 --> 00:53:02,240
...is running around with my old
girlfriend? That's a coincidence.

560
00:53:02,640 --> 00:53:04,640
I knew it was a mistake
to try to help you.

561
00:53:04,840 --> 00:53:07,760
You put me in a car with Tully
because you want Emil Brandt.

562
00:53:08,760 --> 00:53:10,600
- Why?
- My apologies, Jake.

563
00:53:10,760 --> 00:53:13,520
But I'm spending my days
trying to find Adolf Eichmann...

564
00:53:13,520 --> 00:53:15,360
...not filling out trip tickets.

565
00:53:16,080 --> 00:53:18,720
Why don't you get some sleep?
You look like shit.

566
00:53:19,280 --> 00:53:20,280
Thanks for coming in.

567
00:53:22,560 --> 00:53:26,240
We're speaking to you from the end
of a long, smooth runway of an airfield-

568
00:53:26,440 --> 00:53:29,320
- Hi.
- Can I help you, sir?

569
00:53:29,520 --> 00:53:31,240
I need a trip ticket.

570
00:53:31,480 --> 00:53:33,440
That's form 48.

571
00:53:40,280 --> 00:53:44,080
Thank you. Now, if I wanted
to request a specific driver-?

572
00:53:44,080 --> 00:53:48,680
- The same form. Just fill in the name.
- It's a fella I used a few days ago.

573
00:53:48,880 --> 00:53:50,560
Could you pull that trip ticket?

574
00:53:50,760 --> 00:53:53,720
- What's your name, sir?
- Geismer.

575
00:53:58,480 --> 00:54:01,720
G- E-I-S....

576
00:54:10,040 --> 00:54:12,920
- Thank you.
- You're welcome, sir.

577
00:55:53,600 --> 00:55:54,960
Emil Brandt.

578
00:56:54,600 --> 00:56:56,840
Champagne from the cellar
of Admiral Donitz.

579
00:56:57,040 --> 00:56:58,800
Care for some?

580
00:56:59,320 --> 00:57:01,920
- I wouldn't want it to go to waste.
- Size of the bubbles.

581
00:57:02,120 --> 00:57:04,800
Smaller the better,
that's the key to champagne.

582
00:57:05,000 --> 00:57:10,160
This time last year I was in Anzio,
up to my balls in mud.

583
00:57:10,520 --> 00:57:14,240
Six months ago I was freezing
my ass off in the Ardennes.

584
00:57:14,240 --> 00:57:15,600
The good old days.

585
00:57:15,840 --> 00:57:19,520
When you could tell who the bad guy
was by who was shooting at you.

586
00:57:20,720 --> 00:57:22,800
Something on your mind?

587
00:57:24,120 --> 00:57:26,840
You're hiding someone
in a safe house in Kreuzberg.

588
00:57:27,040 --> 00:57:28,560
Who is it?

589
00:57:29,520 --> 00:57:32,400
Lieutenant Schaeffer should be
more careful about who follows him.

590
00:57:32,600 --> 00:57:35,400
I wouldn't blame Schaeffer.
His name was on the trip ticket.

591
00:57:35,600 --> 00:57:38,080
It could be
I'm just a very attentive host.

592
00:57:38,120 --> 00:57:41,960
Either that, or you thought
I could lead you to Emil Brandt.

593
00:58:09,000 --> 00:58:12,440
What do you think this peace conference
is really about, who gets Poland?

594
00:58:12,640 --> 00:58:16,000
The future. That's why everyone's
come to Potsdam.

595
00:58:16,200 --> 00:58:19,000
What do the next hundred years
look like?

596
00:58:19,240 --> 00:58:21,720
All those V-2 rockets that hit London
during the war.

597
00:58:21,960 --> 00:58:23,600
Well, you were there.

598
00:58:24,080 --> 00:58:27,280
If it lasted another year,
that would have been New York...

599
00:58:27,520 --> 00:58:29,960
- ... Chicago.
- What's this got to do...

600
00:58:30,120 --> 00:58:31,520
...with the peace conference?

601
00:58:31,960 --> 00:58:34,680
I thought you might have
recognized him.

602
00:58:35,400 --> 00:58:38,040
Our friend in the safe house...

603
00:58:38,240 --> 00:58:39,480
...is Franz Bettmann.

604
00:58:46,120 --> 00:58:47,200
The Russians get Poland...

605
00:58:47,400 --> 00:58:49,960
- ... and we get the brains.
- In a perfect world...

606
00:58:50,160 --> 00:58:53,720
...doesn't a man like Franz Bettmann
wind up building rockets for our side?

607
00:58:53,920 --> 00:58:55,800
But it's not a perfect world.

608
00:58:55,920 --> 00:58:58,040
It doesn't surprise you
that there are those...

609
00:58:58,240 --> 00:59:00,000
...who don't wish
America well, does it?

610
00:59:01,680 --> 00:59:03,360
And Emil Brandt?

611
00:59:03,560 --> 00:59:04,920
Brandt was Bettmann's secretary.

612
00:59:05,360 --> 00:59:09,680
Like a son to him. Bettmann
wants to bring him along to America.

613
00:59:09,880 --> 00:59:13,520
Awfully sentimental. Hundred thousand
marks for somebody's secretary?

614
00:59:14,040 --> 00:59:17,040
All of them.
As many as we can track down.

615
00:59:17,240 --> 00:59:19,000
Split-level with a Ford in the garage.

616
00:59:19,200 --> 00:59:21,480
Kids in the back yard
playing in the sprinklers.

617
00:59:21,800 --> 00:59:24,520
Strange if you wanted
anything different.

618
00:59:24,560 --> 00:59:26,640
Wives too.

619
00:59:28,080 --> 00:59:30,400
I wouldn't put too much stock
in that SS stuff.

620
00:59:31,280 --> 00:59:35,200
When I was at West Point,
we put a uniform on a mule.

621
01:00:39,520 --> 01:00:41,560
Look at these sleeves
and all this ruching.

622
01:00:41,760 --> 01:00:43,520
Nobody wears
anything like this anymore.

623
01:00:43,720 --> 01:00:47,800
I thought we weren't gonna reminisce.
Your rules. Not that we'd have time.

624
01:00:48,000 --> 01:00:50,800
- Why? What's going on?
- Why didn't you tell me Emil...

625
01:00:51,000 --> 01:00:53,800
- ... was with the rocket program?
- I didn't think it mattered.

626
01:00:53,800 --> 01:00:56,480
He worked directly under Bettmann
and it didn't matter?

627
01:00:56,680 --> 01:00:59,440
- Who told you about Bettmann?
- Muller.

628
01:00:59,640 --> 01:01:01,520
They graduated
from the same polytechnic.

629
01:01:01,560 --> 01:01:03,440
That's why Bettmann hired him.

630
01:01:03,640 --> 01:01:05,040
Why did you talk to Muller?

631
01:01:05,240 --> 01:01:08,840
He has Bettmann in a safe house,
on his way to America to make rockets.

632
01:01:09,040 --> 01:01:10,600
That's why they're looking for Emil.

633
01:01:10,840 --> 01:01:14,200
They're all going, including the wives.
Why didn't you tell me, Lena?

634
01:01:14,400 --> 01:01:16,920
- You know what Bettmann did.
- Everybody knows who he is.

635
01:01:17,120 --> 01:01:20,320
He was famous before the war.
Now, you can either tell me or Bernie.

636
01:01:20,480 --> 01:01:22,640
- He'll be here in two minutes.
- No.

637
01:01:23,440 --> 01:01:26,680
What was Tully selling that was worth
so much money? Some rocket secret?

638
01:01:26,880 --> 01:01:28,200
- No.
- Lena.

639
01:01:28,240 --> 01:01:30,760
- How the rockets were built.
- Is that what's in here?

640
01:01:30,960 --> 01:01:32,200
How they were built?

641
01:01:33,000 --> 01:01:35,040
Lena, please.

642
01:01:37,320 --> 01:01:39,920
A factory inside a mountain.

643
01:01:40,600 --> 01:01:43,760
Tunnels where the American bombs
couldn't reach.

644
01:01:43,760 --> 01:01:45,520
What were once sulfur mines.

645
01:01:45,720 --> 01:01:47,600
Someone had to take them out.

646
01:01:47,760 --> 01:01:50,920
Slave labor. Prisoners, detainees.

647
01:01:51,440 --> 01:01:54,160
That was how they built the rockets.

648
01:01:54,560 --> 01:01:57,040
Emil was asked to calculate
how much to feed them...

649
01:01:57,040 --> 01:02:00,680
...to keep them alive just three months
until the tunnels were completed.

650
01:02:01,000 --> 01:02:04,320
It's here, in his notebooks.

651
01:02:05,640 --> 01:02:08,480
Eight hundred calories a day.

652
01:02:08,520 --> 01:02:12,200
After that, let them die
and bring in new workers.

653
01:02:12,760 --> 01:02:15,400
The correct answer, it turned out.

654
01:02:15,400 --> 01:02:17,200
It was more efficient.

655
01:02:19,320 --> 01:02:23,320
They called it Dora. Camp Dora.

656
01:02:24,040 --> 01:02:26,720
Thirty thousand died in that camp.

657
01:02:26,920 --> 01:02:28,320
Bettmann ran it.

658
01:02:28,520 --> 01:02:30,680
Every detail.

659
01:02:31,400 --> 01:02:35,200
He hanged people from a crane
right outside his office window.

660
01:02:51,560 --> 01:02:54,560
Take the back stairs. Find Danny
and tell him we have to move again.

661
01:02:54,760 --> 01:02:56,320
And, Lena?

662
01:02:57,480 --> 01:02:59,320
Make sure he knows
where I can find you.

663
01:03:10,520 --> 01:03:11,920
She's playing you, Jake.

664
01:03:11,920 --> 01:03:13,800
You have no idea
what you're dealing with.

665
01:03:14,840 --> 01:03:17,480
Muller paid Tully
100,000 marks for Emil Brandt...

666
01:03:17,640 --> 01:03:20,600
...because he worked for the rocket
program. One big happy family.

667
01:03:20,840 --> 01:03:22,640
They're all coming over
to our side now.

668
01:03:22,840 --> 01:03:25,280
Muller's hiding Franz Bettmann
in a safe house.

669
01:03:25,480 --> 01:03:28,200
Of course he is. The Russians
want them worse than we do.

670
01:03:28,240 --> 01:03:30,680
- They're kidnapping them.
- Not from the Russians...

671
01:03:30,880 --> 01:03:33,440
...you dumb fucking cheesehead,
he's hiding him from you.

672
01:03:33,800 --> 01:03:35,880
They built the rockets
in concentration camps.

673
01:03:36,080 --> 01:03:38,760
Slave labor. Bettmann ran it.

674
01:03:41,040 --> 01:03:43,440
I don't wanna call
your girlfriend a liar.

675
01:03:43,480 --> 01:03:46,520
Let's just say I've met 12 people
who swear on their mother...

676
01:03:46,520 --> 01:03:50,320
...they can deliver me Adolf Hitler
if I'll cut them a deal.

677
01:03:50,320 --> 01:03:54,040
Her husband was Bettmann's secretary.
I've seen the notebooks.

678
01:03:55,920 --> 01:03:58,440
Be honest with yourself
for a change, Jake.

679
01:03:58,640 --> 01:04:01,760
Has anything good happened
since you came back?

680
01:05:33,560 --> 01:05:34,800
Can I help you?

681
01:05:35,200 --> 01:05:36,640
A watch, perhaps?

682
01:05:36,840 --> 01:05:39,600
- No, thanks.
- How about a cigarette case?

683
01:05:39,600 --> 01:05:41,160
What happened to you?

684
01:05:41,360 --> 01:05:43,760
An experiment
to see if you can transplant...

685
01:05:43,960 --> 01:05:46,280
...a bone from one man into another.

686
01:05:46,440 --> 01:05:47,760
It turns out you can't.

687
01:05:51,600 --> 01:05:54,720
- Always something worse.
- You can get such stories anywhere.

688
01:05:54,960 --> 01:05:58,200
I have plenty of those.
The Russians trade them for Lugers.

689
01:05:58,560 --> 01:06:00,640
- No, thanks.
- How about a camera?

690
01:06:01,520 --> 01:06:03,480
Rolleiflex.

691
01:06:04,240 --> 01:06:07,400
The old ones used to turn the image
upside-down in the viewfinder.

692
01:06:07,600 --> 01:06:09,280
Little mirror sets it right.

693
01:06:09,480 --> 01:06:12,080
To set things right,
a thing to wish for.

694
01:06:12,120 --> 01:06:14,840
The woman who was just in here,
what did she want?

695
01:06:17,040 --> 01:06:19,000
Nothing. She bought nothing.

696
01:06:19,480 --> 01:06:23,200
I know her. Lena Brandt.
I know she was here for a reason.

697
01:06:24,160 --> 01:06:25,840
Why?

698
01:06:26,040 --> 01:06:27,480
Papers.

699
01:06:27,760 --> 01:06:30,480
She wanted papers
to get out of Germany.

700
01:06:30,680 --> 01:06:33,880
A Persilschein, like the soap.
That's what they call it.

701
01:06:34,280 --> 01:06:37,040
- To wash the sins away.
- Papers for who?

702
01:06:37,680 --> 01:06:39,120
For herself.

703
01:06:39,120 --> 01:06:41,360
What did she do
that she has to wash away?

704
01:06:44,280 --> 01:06:47,320
Better to ask why I would help her.

705
01:06:47,520 --> 01:06:50,160
Me, with what I survived.

706
01:06:53,480 --> 01:06:55,280
I wanna know.

707
01:07:08,880 --> 01:07:10,760
At the Little White House
in Potsdam...

708
01:07:10,920 --> 01:07:14,480
...Generalissimo Stalin of Russia is one
of the first to welcome the president.

709
01:07:14,680 --> 01:07:18,360
As the meeting is recorded
by Signal Corps and newsreel cameras.

710
01:07:22,360 --> 01:07:24,840
Next to join the group
is Prime Minister Churchill...

711
01:07:25,080 --> 01:07:27,480
...who meets
an old conference friend.

712
01:07:30,520 --> 01:07:33,600
The Big Three meetings are held in
Kaiser Wilhelm's former palace.

713
01:07:33,640 --> 01:07:36,680
And President Truman is selected
as chairman of the conference.

714
01:07:36,880 --> 01:07:40,400
Here, the fate of Germany and the end
of Japanese aggression will be settled.

715
01:07:40,600 --> 01:07:42,840
Under the flag
that flew over the White House...

716
01:07:43,040 --> 01:07:46,920
...when we declared war on the Axis,
the president states our aims.

717
01:07:47,840 --> 01:07:51,120
We are here today
to raise the flag of victory...

718
01:07:51,320 --> 01:07:56,560
...over the capital
of our greatest adversary.

719
01:07:56,720 --> 01:08:01,240
Let's not forget
that we are fighting for peace...

720
01:08:01,640 --> 01:08:05,040
...and for the welfare of mankind.

721
01:08:05,200 --> 01:08:10,960
There's not one piece of territory,
or one thing...

722
01:08:11,160 --> 01:08:13,800
...of a monetary nature
that we want out of this war.

723
01:08:14,000 --> 01:08:19,160
We want peace and prosperity
for the world as a whole.

724
01:08:19,360 --> 01:08:22,440
If we can put this
tremendous machine of ours...

725
01:08:22,640 --> 01:08:26,760
...which has made this victory possible,
to work for peace...

726
01:08:26,960 --> 01:08:30,960
...we can look forward to the greatest
age in the history of mankind.

727
01:09:08,320 --> 01:09:11,560
They have a file on her.
I thought Bernie's golem broke into...

728
01:09:11,560 --> 01:09:14,840
...her place looking for Emil,
but it was Lena they were looking for.

729
01:09:15,040 --> 01:09:18,280
That's why she had to get out.
Something she did during the war.

730
01:09:18,480 --> 01:09:21,040
Tully wasn't killed in Potsdam,
he was killed at Muller's.

731
01:09:21,280 --> 01:09:24,320
The body floated with the current.
It didn't have to be someone...

732
01:09:24,520 --> 01:09:27,840
...with access to the conference.
The Russian gun? Get it at a pawnshop.

733
01:09:28,040 --> 01:09:30,520
- It could have been anyone.
- Always something worse.

734
01:09:30,720 --> 01:09:32,120
- Did she ask you?
- What?

735
01:09:32,320 --> 01:09:35,440
- To get her out of Berlin.
- She asked Tully.

736
01:09:35,480 --> 01:09:38,480
You want my advice?
You'll forget all this.

737
01:09:38,720 --> 01:09:41,160
You'll only get hurt here.
Or hurt someone.

738
01:09:41,200 --> 01:09:42,480
- Where is she, Danny?
- Jake.

739
01:09:42,680 --> 01:09:45,080
- Where is she, Danny?
- Jake.

740
01:10:06,040 --> 01:10:08,080
- Where are you going?
- I have someone to meet.

741
01:10:08,280 --> 01:10:09,920
- Who?
- Stop following me.

742
01:10:09,960 --> 01:10:12,640
- What about the curfew?
- Life is inconvenient sometimes.

743
01:10:12,840 --> 01:10:15,240
- It's not safe.
- And always, it seems not safe.

744
01:10:15,400 --> 01:10:17,600
- Who?
- Someone who can get me out of Berlin.

745
01:10:18,080 --> 01:10:19,720
- I'll go with you.
- No.

746
01:10:19,920 --> 01:10:21,840
Tully tried to get you out,
now he's dead.

747
01:10:22,040 --> 01:10:24,880
- Someone is waiting.
- Why is it so important for you to leave?

748
01:10:25,080 --> 01:10:27,600
- Please.
- What are you running away from?

749
01:10:34,840 --> 01:10:37,840
You should never have come back
to Berlin.

750
01:10:51,720 --> 01:10:54,160
Why didn't Jake follow me?

751
01:10:54,160 --> 01:10:56,440
Why didn't he try?

752
01:10:57,920 --> 01:10:59,920
He was scared.

753
01:10:59,960 --> 01:11:02,800
Scared I'd really do it.

754
01:11:02,800 --> 01:11:04,760
That I'd shoot him...

755
01:11:04,960 --> 01:11:07,120
...just like Tully.

756
01:11:08,560 --> 01:11:10,080
All these men...

757
01:11:10,320 --> 01:11:12,360
...they want you to cry in their arms.

758
01:11:13,640 --> 01:11:16,120
I had no more tears.

759
01:11:16,280 --> 01:11:18,880
I knew what I had become.

760
01:11:19,960 --> 01:11:21,840
I had to kill Tully.

761
01:11:22,040 --> 01:11:24,880
He was getting
too close to the truth.

762
01:11:24,880 --> 01:11:27,960
Which was that the only way
out of Berlin for me...

763
01:11:28,160 --> 01:11:30,800
...was to do one thing good.

764
01:11:31,000 --> 01:11:33,240
One thing noble.

765
01:11:33,440 --> 01:11:36,960
Otherwise,
Berlin would just follow me.

766
01:11:38,240 --> 01:11:42,040
A wife should help her husband.

767
01:11:43,080 --> 01:11:45,160
Isn't that noble?

768
01:11:46,120 --> 01:11:48,480
Isn't that good?

769
01:11:53,160 --> 01:11:54,760
Emil.

770
01:14:42,040 --> 01:14:45,440
I'll be candid. I'd think I'm the last
person you'd wanna contact.

771
01:14:46,160 --> 01:14:48,200
Sometimes people surprise you.

772
01:14:49,680 --> 01:14:51,120
Then your husband is alive?

773
01:14:54,720 --> 01:14:58,000
We're going to have to decide
to trust each other, Mrs. Brandt.

774
01:14:58,240 --> 01:15:01,440
To ask to meet me here
in the Russian sector is not a good start.

775
01:15:01,640 --> 01:15:03,600
I'm frightened.

776
01:15:04,680 --> 01:15:06,960
That's not so difficult to understand.

777
01:15:07,440 --> 01:15:11,320
When our Gls liberated Camp Dora,
they found bodies stacked up in a room.

778
01:15:12,080 --> 01:15:13,840
Stopped counting at a thousand.

779
01:15:14,000 --> 01:15:16,640
That was the first thing they found.

780
01:15:17,240 --> 01:15:19,920
There's nothing.
Nothing to link Bettmann to any of it.

781
01:15:20,120 --> 01:15:23,040
Not one sheet of paper,
not one witness.

782
01:15:23,960 --> 01:15:29,080
Your husband sat in
on every single meeting and took notes.

783
01:15:29,560 --> 01:15:32,000
If he were alive...

784
01:15:32,240 --> 01:15:35,080
...it would be extremely significant.

785
01:15:36,040 --> 01:15:39,280
Yes. He's alive.

786
01:15:39,440 --> 01:15:41,240
He's a good German.

787
01:15:41,440 --> 01:15:43,720
He wants to tell the truth
about Camp Dora.

788
01:15:43,920 --> 01:15:46,400
What is it you want, Mrs. Brandt?

789
01:15:48,360 --> 01:15:51,040
I want to get out of Berlin.

790
01:15:51,240 --> 01:15:53,360
Without my husband.

791
01:15:54,240 --> 01:15:55,920
Does he know that?

792
01:15:58,160 --> 01:15:59,520
No.

793
01:16:01,120 --> 01:16:04,000
If I let you go,
I'm part of the same hypocrisy as Muller.

794
01:16:04,240 --> 01:16:05,880
But you'll do it.

795
01:16:05,920 --> 01:16:08,440
Bring him in. Bring your husband in.

796
01:16:08,640 --> 01:16:10,560
We'll talk about it.

797
01:16:12,400 --> 01:16:14,480
Why'd you leave the money on him?

798
01:16:15,040 --> 01:16:17,960
Tully. Did you panic?

799
01:16:18,160 --> 01:16:20,480
I don't know
what you're talking about.

800
01:16:26,680 --> 01:16:28,920
You sure you wouldn't be better off
staying put?

801
01:16:28,960 --> 01:16:30,920
I'm nervous
someone followed me here.

802
01:16:31,160 --> 01:16:33,600
I'm close, Danny,
really close to getting out.

803
01:16:33,640 --> 01:16:35,800
That's when people get careless.

804
01:16:36,000 --> 01:16:39,480
Because you can trust Jake,
if that's who you're worried about.

805
01:16:40,240 --> 01:16:42,160
Have you got somewhere
you can put me?

806
01:16:42,360 --> 01:16:44,480
I've got a Kino
I bought in the French sector.

807
01:16:44,680 --> 01:16:46,480
You know how they are about cinema.

808
01:16:46,680 --> 01:16:50,040
Matinee only until the curfew's lifted,
but it still turns a dollar.

809
01:16:50,080 --> 01:16:53,240
After that,
I'm fresh out of places to park you.

810
01:16:58,440 --> 01:17:01,320
I'm going to need some money
when I get to London.

811
01:17:01,520 --> 01:17:03,640
You got a john for me? A rich one?

812
01:17:03,840 --> 01:17:07,320
I've got a bloke in the club
who'll give you a thousand marks.

813
01:17:08,240 --> 01:17:09,520
Thinking about it?

814
01:17:09,720 --> 01:17:14,000
When I met you,
you'd have a go for a can of tuna.

815
01:18:02,720 --> 01:18:04,240
Hello?

816
01:18:39,320 --> 01:18:41,440
Don't let me interrupt you.

817
01:18:47,160 --> 01:18:49,120
A thousand marks.

818
01:18:49,320 --> 01:18:51,400
That's the deal, isn't it?

819
01:18:55,400 --> 01:18:58,440
You want it straight
or something special?

820
01:18:58,440 --> 01:19:00,400
What's special?

821
01:19:00,600 --> 01:19:03,040
Whatever you want.

822
01:19:03,240 --> 01:19:06,320
- How did Tully like it?
- Rough.

823
01:19:10,520 --> 01:19:12,280
You going to take off your clothes?

824
01:19:15,760 --> 01:19:17,640
You do it.

825
01:19:41,680 --> 01:19:43,320
Forget it.

826
01:19:44,680 --> 01:19:46,720
You keep the money.

827
01:19:47,320 --> 01:19:50,440
No. I want to.

828
01:19:53,760 --> 01:19:56,040
I would have gotten you out.

829
01:19:57,680 --> 01:19:59,360
I still would.

830
01:20:02,000 --> 01:20:05,280
You can never really get out of Berlin.

831
01:25:30,920 --> 01:25:32,280
I followed you.

832
01:25:32,520 --> 01:25:34,560
It's a good thing too.

833
01:25:35,440 --> 01:25:37,280
Go down to the Zoo Station.

834
01:25:37,520 --> 01:25:40,760
Find Danny and wait there until I get
enough money to get both of you out.

835
01:25:42,520 --> 01:25:44,280
Pal, I'm the one sticking my neck out.

836
01:25:44,480 --> 01:25:46,320
We're supposed to meet
Hauptmann Teitel.

837
01:25:48,080 --> 01:25:51,320
Do I have to draw a picture? Someone
got to him. Even Bernie they got to.

838
01:26:04,040 --> 01:26:06,640
Stand over there like you're waiting.
You answer the door.

839
01:26:21,400 --> 01:26:23,120
Mrs. Brandt.

840
01:26:23,960 --> 01:26:25,320
And this must be the famous-

841
01:26:30,560 --> 01:26:32,000
Go!

842
01:27:13,880 --> 01:27:15,440
Help him.

843
01:27:29,280 --> 01:27:30,320
Go.

844
01:30:15,800 --> 01:30:17,800
How's your shoulder?

845
01:30:23,000 --> 01:30:25,160
The nurses are very kind.

846
01:30:25,880 --> 01:30:28,880
We were told that, if we found you,
your husband would follow.

847
01:30:29,040 --> 01:30:31,160
That he was devoted to you.

848
01:30:31,400 --> 01:30:33,760
Now I understand why.

849
01:30:34,560 --> 01:30:35,920
You're a lovely woman.

850
01:30:36,560 --> 01:30:39,120
Remind me of the gals back home.

851
01:30:46,480 --> 01:30:48,520
Schenectady.

852
01:30:48,680 --> 01:30:49,720
You'd like it there.

853
01:30:49,920 --> 01:30:52,040
Lots of good German folk.

854
01:30:52,280 --> 01:30:54,480
The Sauerfleisch
would make you forget Berlin.

855
01:30:54,720 --> 01:30:58,040
Forgetting would be better
than the Sauerfleisch.

856
01:30:59,720 --> 01:31:01,680
Well, forgetting's a two-way street.

857
01:31:01,840 --> 01:31:05,360
There are things you wanna forget
and things we wanna forget.

858
01:31:07,160 --> 01:31:10,160
Where are your husband's documents,
Mrs. Brandt?

859
01:31:10,200 --> 01:31:11,600
We can't seem to find them.

860
01:31:12,920 --> 01:31:16,360
Oh, they're not with my other things?

861
01:31:16,560 --> 01:31:18,640
You know they're not.

862
01:31:19,640 --> 01:31:22,560
I don't know,
I can't remember anything.

863
01:31:23,560 --> 01:31:28,400
The medicine they've given me,
it's making me feel all dizzy.

864
01:31:34,560 --> 01:31:37,000
Most important thing right now...

865
01:31:37,960 --> 01:31:40,200
...is for you to get well.

866
01:31:44,120 --> 01:31:45,800
Mrs. Brandt.

867
01:31:54,200 --> 01:31:57,080
- What the hell are you doing here?
- Why, Mr. Geismer.

868
01:31:57,320 --> 01:32:00,920
It's after visiting hours, but I guess
some people just can't follow the rules.

869
01:32:01,120 --> 01:32:03,000
Leave her alone. I mean it.

870
01:32:03,240 --> 01:32:05,960
I came here to make sure
she makes the right decision.

871
01:32:06,160 --> 01:32:07,680
You really wanna push me?

872
01:32:07,680 --> 01:32:09,400
I wouldn't.

873
01:32:10,040 --> 01:32:13,160
You don't have those documents,
do you, Jake?

874
01:32:17,440 --> 01:32:20,680
You've seen what months of bombing
can do to a city.

875
01:32:21,160 --> 01:32:24,000
Imagine one bomb
could do the same thing.

876
01:32:24,200 --> 01:32:25,680
One bomb.

877
01:32:25,880 --> 01:32:29,520
Stick it on the end of a rocket,
press a button here, goes off over there.

878
01:32:29,760 --> 01:32:31,720
Anywhere, halfway around the world.

879
01:32:31,960 --> 01:32:33,680
That's the future.

880
01:32:33,880 --> 01:32:35,720
The future of mankind's in our hands.

881
01:32:35,920 --> 01:32:39,240
It's our destiny.
Hell, don't you read the papers?

882
01:33:08,000 --> 01:33:10,960
- How'd you get in here?
- Who got to you? Was it Muller?

883
01:33:11,160 --> 01:33:13,760
- Do I need to call an MP?
- Not just yet.

884
01:33:13,920 --> 01:33:15,240
What's "Overcast"?

885
01:33:16,680 --> 01:33:19,520
- Who told you about Overcast?
- Is it a code name?

886
01:33:19,720 --> 01:33:21,600
What's it got to do with Lena?

887
01:33:22,360 --> 01:33:26,000
Come on, Bernie, trot out one of your
atrocity stories to get me off your back.

888
01:33:26,160 --> 01:33:28,520
I had nothing to do with what happened
to Emil Brandt.

889
01:33:28,720 --> 01:33:30,960
You're the only one that knew
about me and Lena.

890
01:33:31,160 --> 01:33:32,400
So what? They got to me.

891
01:33:33,560 --> 01:33:35,440
Least I got something for it.

892
01:33:35,680 --> 01:33:40,040
I get to hang a half dozen Nazis
they wanted to just send to jail.

893
01:33:40,200 --> 01:33:42,520
Not like your girlfriend, though.

894
01:33:43,720 --> 01:33:46,440
She got everything she wanted,
didn't she?

895
01:33:46,600 --> 01:33:48,000
She's good at that.

896
01:33:48,480 --> 01:33:52,360
Well, you can tell your boy Gunther
that he left one big, swinging loose end.

897
01:33:52,560 --> 01:33:55,360
Lena doesn't have Emil's documents.

898
01:33:55,560 --> 01:33:57,360
I do.

899
01:33:57,560 --> 01:34:00,040
- Don't do it, Jake.
- I'll call you later for your quote.

900
01:34:00,240 --> 01:34:02,840
You never saw Lena's file, did you?

901
01:34:04,640 --> 01:34:06,560
Yeah. You get me those documents...

902
01:34:06,800 --> 01:34:09,600
...or I'll put her in jail
for the rest of her life.

903
01:34:09,600 --> 01:34:12,240
I have everything I need
and then some.

904
01:34:12,840 --> 01:34:15,120
Don't think I won't do it.

905
01:34:20,960 --> 01:34:24,240
If I give you those documents,
then she leaves with me.

906
01:34:24,440 --> 01:34:27,720
- Breimer's already taken care of that.
- Not with Bettmann. With me.

907
01:34:27,720 --> 01:34:30,720
Anyplace she wants to go.
Anyplace I wanna take her.

908
01:34:33,640 --> 01:34:37,560
You've been wrong every step
of the way, Jake. Why stop now?

909
01:34:41,120 --> 01:34:42,840
What's in her file, Bernie?

910
01:34:47,320 --> 01:34:49,400
Why don't you ask her?

911
01:35:14,400 --> 01:35:17,560
- You have your papers?
- They won't stop me. I'm with you.

912
01:35:17,560 --> 01:35:20,880
- Where are they?
- They're in my purse.

913
01:35:21,080 --> 01:35:23,080
There's something wrong.

914
01:35:25,120 --> 01:35:26,520
Jake?

915
01:35:26,720 --> 01:35:30,320
Why was it so important
to get Emil out of Berlin?

916
01:35:30,520 --> 01:35:32,720
And why does Bernie
have a file on you?

917
01:35:32,920 --> 01:35:37,720
He had a file on everyone. I told you,
I was the wife of an SS man.

918
01:35:37,920 --> 01:35:40,680
Hitler put the rocket program
under the SS two years ago.

919
01:35:40,720 --> 01:35:44,240
That's what you told me. That as the
wife of an SS man, you were exempt.

920
01:35:44,480 --> 01:35:46,680
That's true. I told you the truth.

921
01:35:46,880 --> 01:35:49,960
How many Jews
were still in Germany in 1943?

922
01:35:50,200 --> 01:35:54,000
By the time Emil could help you,
you should have been deported or dead.

923
01:35:58,960 --> 01:36:02,000
There were not so many.
You are right.

924
01:36:02,880 --> 01:36:06,200
So when they caught me,
I turned that to my advantage.

925
01:36:06,400 --> 01:36:10,000
I used the skills you taught me.
When I worked for you, for the newspaper.

926
01:36:10,200 --> 01:36:12,880
Watch, observe.

927
01:36:13,120 --> 01:36:14,920
The stupid risks they would take-

928
01:36:15,160 --> 01:36:19,160
Lunch at Aschinger's. -just to remind
themselves they were still human.

929
01:36:22,720 --> 01:36:24,720
I found 12.

930
01:36:27,680 --> 01:36:31,000
I turned 12 people
over to the Gestapo.

931
01:36:31,200 --> 01:36:33,280
That's how I survived.

932
01:36:33,640 --> 01:36:35,320
It was all to survive.

933
01:36:35,320 --> 01:36:37,200
Everything.

934
01:36:49,360 --> 01:36:51,360
Now you know.

935
01:36:53,000 --> 01:36:55,480
The last piece in your puzzle.

